content.thinking:
Good analysis. Now I understand the full picture:

1. All locale-aware config fields (`title`, `description`, `footerText`, `hero.*`, `features.*.name`, `footer.builtWith.text`) are consumed through `resolveLocaleValue(value, lang)` or `resolveLocale(value)`.

2. `resolveLocaleValue` already handles plain strings:
```typescript
export function resolveLocaleValue(value: string | Record<string, string>, lang: string): string {
  if (typeof value === 'string') return value;
  return value[lang] || value.en || Object.values(value)[0] || '';


}
```

3. So plain strings **already work** — a user can write `title: "My Blog"` instead of `title: { en: "My Blog", zh: "我的博客" }` and everything just works.

The real problem is that the sample config always demonstrates the object form, which causes TypeScript to infer the type as the object shape rather than the union type, even though the function accepts both. The type inference doesn't match what the function actually supports at runtime.

When a user switches from the object form to a plain string, TypeScript correctly infers it as `string`, which is assignable to the `string | Record<string, string>` union the function expects. So the implementation is already backward compatible — users just don't realize they can use plain strings because the examples don't show it.

I'm weighing whether to update the default template to use plain strings for accessibility, or keep the locale-object format to showcase the framework's i18n capabilities. The best approach might be keeping the current template but adding a comment that clarifies plain strings work when i18n isn't needed. I should present both approaches to the user so they can decide which direction works better for their use case.

